* 1791 – Population: 51,307.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1792
** [[Sociedad Económica de los Amigos del País de la Habana]] established.<ref name=Learned1908 />
** Palace built.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1794
** [[Consulate of the Sea|Consulado]] (merchant guild) established.<ref>{{citation |author=Ralph Lee Woodward Jr. |chapter= Merchant Guilds |title= Encyclopedia of World Trade |editor= Cynthia Clark Northrup |publisher= Routledge |year= 2013 |orig-year=2005 |isbn=9780765682680 }}</ref>
** Charity and Maternity Asylum opens.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}

==19th century==
* 1810 – Hurricane.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1811 – Population: 94,023.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1813 – ''[[El Diario de la Marina|El Lucero de la Habana]]'' newspaper begins publication.
* 1817
** Botanical Gardens established.{{sfn|Lejeune|1996}}
** [[Floridita|La Piña de Plata]] eatery in business.
* 1828 – El Templete chapel built in the Plaza de Armas.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1832 – ''[[El Diario de la Marina|El Noticioso y Lucero de la Habana]]'' newspaper begins publication.
* 1834 – President's Palace built.{{sfn|Baedeker|1909}}
* 1835
** Fernando VII aqueduct constructed.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
** Mercado de Cristina (market) built on [[Plaza Vieja, Havana|Plaza Vieja]].{{sfn|Barclay|1993}}
* 1837 – Railway (Havana-[[Bejucal]]), Mercado de Cristina, and city jail{{sfn|Britannica|1910}} constructed.
* 1838 – [[Teatro Tacón]] opens.{{sfn|Bonavía|2003}}
* 1844
** Liceo Artistico y Literario de la Habana (lyceum) founded.{{sfn|Ramírez|1891}}<ref>{{citation |title=Catálogo de los fondos del Liceo Artístico y Literario de la Habana |year=1944 |publisher=[[Archivo Nacional de la República de Cuba]] |author={{Interlanguage link multi|Joaquín Llaverías Martínez|es}} |language=es }}</ref>
** {{Interlanguage link multi|Palacio de Aldama|es}} built.{{sfn|Philippou|2014}}
* 1846 – [[Great Havana Hurricane of 1846|Great Havana Hurricane]].
* 1847 – Premiere of [[Giovanni Bottesini|Bottesini]]'s opera ''Cristoforo Colombo''.<ref>{{citation |author=[[Robert Stevenson (musicologist)|Robert Murrell Stevenson]] |chapter=Havana |title=New Grove Dictionary of Opera |location= New York |year= 1992 |isbn=0935859926 }}</ref>
* 1853
** Susini cigarette factory in operation.<ref name="Robertson2011" />
** ''[[Revista de la Habana]]'' literary magazine begins publication.{{sfn|Bonavía|2003}}
* 1854 – [[Colegio de Belén]] founded.<ref name=Learned1908 />
* 1856 – Hotel Inglaterra built.{{sfn|Lejeune|1996}}
* 1861 – [[Cuban Academy of Sciences|Royal Academy of Medical, Physical, and Natural Sciences]] established.<ref name=Learned1908>{{cite book |title=Handbook of Learned Societies and Institutions: America |year=1908|publisher= [[Carnegie Institution of Washington]] |location=USA |chapter= Cuba |chapterurl= http://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t5t72q98c?urlappend=%3Bseq=490 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=National Science in a Colonial Context: The Royal Academy of Sciences of Havana, 1861–1898 |author= Pedro M. Pruna |journal= Isis |volume=85 |year=1994 |jstor=235461 | doi = 10.1086/356890 }}</ref>
* 1863
** [[Fuente de la India]] (fountain) installed in Parque Central.
** City walls dismantled.
* 1868
** ''El Ansador Comercial'' begins publication.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
** [[Colon Cemetery, Havana|Colon Cemetery]] inaugurated.<ref>{{Citation |url = http://openlibrary.org/books/OL22892116M/The_Republic_of_Cuba |author = Bankers' Loan and Securities Company, New Orleans |publication-date = 1916 |publication-place = New Orleans |title = The Republic of Cuba }}</ref>
* 1871 – 27 November: Students [[Ten Years' War|executed]].{{sfn|Baedeker|1909}}<sup>([[:es:Fusilamiento de los Ocho Estudiantes de Medicina|es]])</sup>
* 1876 – Hotel Pasaje built.{{sfn|Fornias|1996}}
* 1877
** Villalba palace built.{{sfn|Lejeune|1996}}
** Payret Theatre opens.<ref name=Romera1887>{{Citation |publisher = D. Cortezo y ca. |publication-place = Barcelona |title = Cuba, Puerto-Rico y Filipinas |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=FlwzAQAAIAAJ |language=Spanish |author = Waldo Jiménez de la Romera |publication-date = 1887 |oclc = 3153821 }}</ref>
* 1878
** [[Acueducto de Albear]] inaugurated.
** City becomes part of [[La Habana Province]].
* 1880 – Colegio de Abogados de La Habana (bar association) founded.<ref name=Learned1908 />
* 1881 – Jane Theater-Circus built.{{sfn|Lejeune|1996}}
* 1882 – School of arts and trades opens.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1884 – ''La Lucha'' newspaper begins publication.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1888 – ''La Discusion'' newspaper begins publication.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1889 – Population: 200,000.<ref>{{Citation |publisher = Blacke & Son, Limited |publication-place = London |title = Commercial Geography |author = Karl August Zehden |publication-date = 1889 }}</ref>
* 1890 – Alhambra Theatre opens.<ref name=thomas2008>{{Citation |publisher = University of Illinois Press |isbn = 9780252033315 |title = Cuban Zarzuela: Performing Race and Gender on Havana's Lyric Stage |url = http://openlibrary.org/books/OL10227809M/Cuban_Zarzuela |author = Susan Thomas |publication-date = 2008 |id = 0252033310 }}</ref>
* 1894 – [[Manzana de Gómez]] built.{{sfn|Lejeune|1996}}
* 1898 – 15 February: [[USS Maine (ACR-1)|United States Navy Ship Maine]] explosion.<ref name=NYT-OnThisDay>{{citation |work=New York Times |url= http://learning.blogs.nytimes.com/on-this-day/ |title= On This Day |accessdate=1 June 2015 }}</ref>
* 1899 – U.S. military occupation begins.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}

==20th century==
[[File:1909 Habana map by Baedeker.png|thumb|right|Map of Havana, 1909]]

===1900s–1940s===
* 1901
** {{req|Biblioteca Nacional José Martí}} (library) established.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
** [[Malecón, Havana|Malecón]] (esplanade) construction begins.
* 1902
** 20 May: U.S. occupation of Cuba ends.
** ''{{req|El Mundo (Cuba)}}''{{sfn|Britannica|1910}} and ''Tierra'' newspapers begin publication.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Havana Hub: Cuban Anarchism, Radical Media and the Trans-Caribbean Anarchist Network, 1902–1915 |author=Kirwin R. Shaffer |journal= Caribbean Studies |volume= 37 |year= 2009 |jstor=25702369 }}</ref>
* 1905 – Petroleum refinery in operation.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
* 1907
** Palace of the Association of Store Clerks built.{{sfn|Lejeune|1996}}
** Population: 297,159.{{sfn|Britannica|1910}}
** Sociedad de Ingenieros y Arquitectos de Cuba (engineering society) headquartered in city.<ref name=Learned1908 />
* 1908
** [[Partido Independiente de Color]] (political party) founded in Havana.<ref name=Appiah2005>{{cite book|editor1=[[Kwame Anthony Appiah]] |editor2=[[Henry Louis Gates]] |title=Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African American Experience|year=2005|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-517055-9 |edition=2nd |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=TMZMAgAAQBAJ }}</ref>
** ''Bohemia'' magazine begins publication.<ref name="Balderston2000">{{cite book|editor1=Daniel Balderston|editor2= [[Mike Gonzalez (historian)|Mike Gonzalez]] |editor3= Ana M. Lopez |title=Encyclopedia of Contemporary Latin American and Caribbean Cultures|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kp6FAgAAQBAJ|year= 2000|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-78852-1}}</ref>
** [[Hotel Sevilla]] built.
* 1909 – [[Lonja del Comercio building]] (stock exchange) and {{Interlanguage link multi|Hotel Plaza|es|3=Hotel Plaza (La Habana)}} constructed.{{sfn|Lejeune|1996}}
* 1910 – Pimp [[Alberto Yarini]] is killed in the San Isidro barrio of [[Old Havana]].
* 1913
** [[Museo Nacional de Bellas Artes de La Habana|National Museum of Fine Arts of Havana]] founded.
** ''[[El Heraldo de Cuba]]'' newspaper begins publication.{{sfn|Sanger|1919}}
* 1917
** [[Manzana de Gómez]] shopping arcade built.{{sfn|Bonavía|2003}}
** Club Atenas organized.<ref name=Appiah2005 />
* 1919
** Florida West Indies Airways begins flights to/from [[Key West]], USA.<ref name="Robertson2011">{{cite book|author=Patrick Robertson|title= Robertson's Book of Firsts |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TEEaCrPiWsC|year= 2011|publisher=Bloomsbury |isbn=978-1-60819-738-5}}</ref>
** Population: 363,506 city; 697,583 [[La Habana Province|province]].<ref>{{cite book |title=[[Statesman's Year-Book]] |year=1921 |location=London |publisher= Macmillan and Co.|chapter= Cuba |chapterurl= http://hdl.handle.net/2027/njp.32101072368440?urlappend=%3Bseq=836 }}</ref>
* 1920
** Palace of the Provincial Government built.{{sfn|Lejeune|1996}}
** Biblioteca Municipal (library)<ref name=Valdes2005>{{citation |url=http://bvs.sld.cu/revistas/aci/vol14_1_06/aci10106.htm |language=es |title=Breve reseña sobre la biblioteca pública en Cuba antes de 1959 |author=Miguel Viciedo Valdés |work=[[Acimed]] |issn=1024-9435 |publisher=Centro Nacional de Informacion de Ciencias Medicas |location=Havana |year=2005 |volume=14 |number=1 }}</ref> and [[Ruston Academy]]<ref name=MiamiHeritage /> established.
* 1923 – {{Interlanguage link multi|Parish of the Sacred Heart of Jesus and St. Ignatius of Loyola|es|3=Parroquia del Sagrado del Corazón de Jesús y San Ignacio de Loyola|lt=Church of the Sacred Heart of Jesus}} built.
* 1925 [[Instituto Técnico Militar|Colegio de Belen]], designed by [[Leonardo Morales y Pedroso]] is built.
* 1927 – Regina Theatre<ref name=thomas2008 /> and Centro Asturiano open.{{sfn|Lejeune|1996}}
* 1928
** January–February: [[Pan-American Conference]] held in Havana.
** {{Interlanguage link multi|Parque de la Fraternidad Americana|es}} (park) and [[Amadeo Roldán Theater|Teatro Auditorium]]{{sfn|Bonavía|2003}} inaugurated.
* 1929 – [[National Capitol Building (Havana)|National Capitol Building]] constructed.{{sfn|Bonavía|2003}}
* 1930
** [[José Martí International Airport|Rancho Boyeros Airport]] begins operating.
** [[Bacardi Building (Havana)|Bacardi Building]] constructed.<ref name=MMA-ca11>{{cite web |url= http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/ht/?period=11&region=ca#/Key-Events |title= Mexico and Central America, 1900 A.D.: Key Events |work= Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History |publisher=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] |location=New York |accessdate=1 May 2014 }}</ref>
* 1934 – Orquesta de Cámara de La Habana (musical group) formed.<ref name="Balderston2000" />
* 1938 – {{Interlanguage link multi|Office of the Historian of Havana|es|3=Oficina del Historiador de La Habana}} created; {{Interlanguage link multi|Emilio Roig de Leuchsenring|es}} becomes city historian.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ohch.cu/oficina-del-historiador/ |accessdate=October 3, 2016 |language=es |title=Oficina del Historiador |publisher=Dirección de Patrimonio Cultural |location=Havana }}</ref>
* 1939
** [[Tropicana Club]] in business.
** [[Cuban Baseball Hall of Fame]] inaugurated.
** [[Lyceum and Lawn Tennis Club]] formed.<ref name=MiamiHeritage>{{cite web |title=Cuban Heritage Collection |publisher=University of Miami Libraries |url=http://merrick.library.miami.edu/digitalprojects/chc.php |accessdate=14 January 2013 }}</ref>
* 1945 – [[International Air Transport Association]] founded in Havana.
* 1946
** [[Havana Conference]] held.
** [[Manuel Fernandez Supervielle]] becomes mayor.{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}
* 1948 – [[Cuban National Ballet]] founded.

===1950s–1990s===
* 1953 – [[Iglesia de Jesús de Miramar]] (church) and [[Embassy of the United States, Havana|Embassy of the United States]] built.
* 1956 – [[FOCSA Building]] constructed.
* 1957
** 13 March: [[Anticommunist]] Revolutionary Directorate attempts coup.
** {{Interlanguage link multi|Palacio de la Revolución|es|3=Palacio de la Revolución|lt=Supreme Court}} building constructed on [[Plaza Cívica (Havana)|Plaza Cívica]].{{sfn|Scarpaci et al.|2002}}
** [[Coliseo de la Ciudad Deportiva]] (arena) opens.
* 1958
** November: [[Rafael Guas Inclán]] elected mayor.
** [[José Martí Memorial]] erected in Plaza Cívica.
* 1959
** January: [[Cuban Revolution|Revolutionary forces]] take city.<ref name=bbc-timeline>{{citation |work=BBC News |title=Cuba Profile: Timeline |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-19576144 |accessdate=1 September 2015 }}</ref>
** Instituto Nacional de Ahorro y Vivienda (housing agency) headquartered in Havana.<ref>{{cite journal |author1= Ruslan Muñoz Hernández |author2= Gabriela González González |language=es |volume=30 |year= 2015 |doi= 10.4067/S0718-83582015000200004 |title= Labor desarrollada por el Instituto Nacional de Ahorro y Vivienda (INAV) en La Habana (1959–1962) |trans-title=The Work of the National Institute of Savings and Housing (INAV) in Havana (1959–1962) |journal= [[Revista INVI]] |location=Chile }}</ref>
** Plaza Cívica renamed "[[Plaza de la Revolución]]".
* 1960 – [[International Ballet Festival of Havana]] begins.
* 1961
** Cuban [[Ministry of the Interior (Cuba)|Ministry of the Interior]] headquartered in Havana.
** [[Instituto Tecnico Militar]] established.
* 1962 – [[Cuban National Ballet School]] established.
* 1963 – [[Cuban Journalists Union]] headquartered in Havana.<ref name=Europa2002 />
* 1964
** [[Jaime Lucas Ortega y Alamino]] becomes Catholic [[archbishop of Havana]].
** Population: 940,700 city; 1,517,700 urban agglomeration.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1960_round.htm |title=Demographic Yearbook 1965 |year=1966 |publisher=[[Statistical Office of the United Nations]] |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants }}</ref>
* 1965
** {{Interlanguage link multi|Palacio de la Revolución|es}} in use as headquarters of the Communist Party.
** [[International School of Havana]] established.
* 1968 – {{Interlanguage link multi|Jardín botánico Nacional de Cuba|es}} (garden) established.<ref name=botanic>{{cite web |url=http://www.bgci.org/garden_search.php?action=Find&ftrCountry=CU |title=Garden Search: Cuba |publisher= [[Botanic Gardens Conservation International]] |location=London |accessdate=1 September 2015 }}</ref>
* 1970 - Population: 1,008,500 city; 1,751,216 urban agglomeration.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1970_round.htm |title=Demographic Yearbook 1975 |year=1976 |author=[[United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs]], Statistical Office |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital city and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants |pages=253-279 }}</ref>
* 1971 – [[Danza Contemporanea de Cuba]] active.
* 1975 – December: 1st Congress of the Communist Party of Cuba held in Havana.
* 1976 – [[Arroyo Naranjo, Cuba|Arroyo Naranjo]], [[Boyeros, Cuba|Boyeros]], [[Centro Habana, Cuba|Centro Habana]], [[Cerro, Cuba|Cerro]], [[Cotorro, Cuba|Cotorro]], [[Diez de Octubre, Cuba|Diez de Octubre]], [[Guanabacoa, Cuba|Guanabacoa]], [[La Habana del Este, Cuba|La Habana del Este]], [[La Habana Vieja, Cuba|La Habana Vieja]], [[La Lisa, Cuba|La Lisa]], [[Marianao, Cuba|Marianao]], [[Playa, Cuba|Playa]], [[Plaza de la Revolución, Cuba|Plaza de la Revolución]], [[Regla, Cuba|Regla]], [[San Miguel del Padrón, Cuba|San Miguel del Padrón]] administrative [[Municipalities of Cuba|municipalities]] created.
* 1977 – {{req|Ministerio de Cultura de la República de Cuba}}'s Editorial Letras Cubanas publishing house headquartered in Havana.<ref name=Europa2002 />
* 1978 – City hosts [[World Festival of Youth and Students]].
* 1979
** [[Havana Film Festival]] begins.
** {{Interlanguage link multi|Palacio de las Convenciones|es}} built.
* 1982
** [[Old Havana]] designated an UNESCO [[World Heritage Site]].<ref name=unesco>{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/204 |title=Old Havana and its Fortification System |work= World Heritage Centre |publisher=United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization |accessdate=1 June 2015 }}</ref>
** [[Havana's International Book Fair|Havana International Book Fair]] begins.
* 1983 – {{Interlanguage link multi|Centro de Investigaciones Psicológicas y Sociológicas|es}} headquartered in Havana.
* 1984 – [[Havana Biennial|Havana Biennial Art Exhibition]] begins.
* 1987
** [[Grupo para el Desarrollo Integral de la Capital]] (urban planning group) formed.{{sfn|Scarpaci et al.|2002}}
** [[Embassy of Russia in Havana|Russian embassy]] built.<ref>{{citation |work=Financial Times |date=31 October 2014 |url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/2e030b12-5b70-11e4-a674-00144feab7de.html |title= Demolition dreams: the world’s ‘worst’ buildings }}</ref>
** [[Instituto de Historia de Cuba]] headquartered in Havana.
* 1991
** [[Estadio Panamericano, Havana|Estadio Panamericano]] (stadium) opens.
** [[1991 Pan American Games]] held in Havana.
* 1993 - Population: 2,175,888 city (estimate).<ref>{{cite book |url= https://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/1990_round.htm |title=1995 Demographic Yearbook |year=1997 |author=United Nations Department for Economic and Social Information and Policy Analysis, Statistics Division |location=New York |chapter=Population of capital cities and cities of 100,000 and more inhabitants |pages=262-321 }}</ref>
* 1994
** [[August 1994 protest in Cuba]].
** Bán Rarra group active.<ref name="Bodenheimer2015">{{cite book|author= Rebecca M. Bodenheimer |title= Geographies of Cubanidad: Place, Race, and Musical Performance in Contemporary Cuba|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lRxlCgAAQBAJ|year=2015|publisher= [[University Press of Mississippi]] |location=USA |isbn=978-1-62674-684-8}}</ref>
** [[Meliá Cohiba Hotel]] in business.
* 1998 – January: Catholic [[List of pastoral visits of Pope John Paul II outside Italy|Pope visits]] Havana.
* 1999 – Population: 2,189,716 city; 2,891,500 province.<ref name=Europa2002>{{cite book|title=South America, Central America and the Caribbean 2002|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o9ODxqsr-dIC|year=2001|publisher=[[Europa Publications]]|isbn=978-1-85743-121-6 |series=Regional Surveys of the World }}</ref>

==21st century==
* 2001 – Ballet Rakatan founded.
* 2003
** [[Damas de Blanco]] protest begins.
** [[Juan Contino Aslán]] becomes mayor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elmundo.es/america/blogs/90-millas/2009/11/02/el-alcalde-invisible.html |language=Spanish |title= El alcalde invisible |date=2 November 2009 |work=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |location=Spain }}</ref>
* 2005 – December: [[World Federation of Trade Unions|World Trade Union Congress]] held in city.<ref name="Green2004">{{cite book|author=Richard Green|title=Chronology of International Organizations |year=2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-35590-6 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=IQQSBAAAQBAJ }}</ref>
* 2011
** April: [[6th Congress of the Communist Party of Cuba]] held in Havana.
** [[Marta Hernández Romero]] becomes mayor.
* 2012 – Population: 2,105,291.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/dyb2013.htm |work=Demographic Yearbook 2013 |publisher=[[United Nations Statistics Division]] |title=Population of Capital Cities and Cities of 100,000 or More Inhabitants }}</ref>
* 2014
** Fábrica de Arte Cubano cultural space established.
** Population: 2,121,871.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/dyb/dyb2014.htm |work=Demographic Yearbook 2014 |publisher= United Nations Statistics Division |title=Population of Capital Cities and Cities of 100,000 or More Inhabitants }}</ref>
* 2015
** January: [[United States–Cuban Thaw|United States–Cuban talks]] held in Havana.<ref name=bbc-timeline /><ref name=Register2016>{{citation |title=[[Annual Register]] |location=UK |issn=0266-6170 |year=2016 |edition=257 |publisher=ProQuest |subscription=yes |chapter=Chronicle of 2015 }}</ref>
** September: Catholic [[List of pastoral visits of Pope Francis outside Italy|pope visits]] city.<ref>{{citation |work=BBC News |date= 20 September 2015 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-34307121 |title= Cuba: Pope Francis celebrates Mass before thousands }}</ref>
* 2016
** March: U.S. president Obama [[List of presidential trips made by Barack Obama during 2016#March|visits]] Havana.
** April: 7th [[Communist Party of Cuba#Congresses|Congress]] of the Communist Party of Cuba held in Havana.

